abstract = "Summary Through a wide series of expressions such as e-health, gerontechnology, telemedicine, assistive technology, etc., the field of technology more and more asserts a vocation to support, restore, or increase what we commonly call autonomy. This article returns to the autonomy concept, and evokes the plethora of technologies (through Internet, mobile health, sensors, cognitive technologies, serious games, robotics, exoskeleton, and many others) that are currently emerging, in order to examine the type of autonomy they intend to favour. It questions also the Silver economy, whose purpose is to build an economical development resulting from the virtuous circle which articulates elders needs for autonomy, the ageing challenges, industrial products, public and private stakeholders, family and professional caregivers, and need for a sustainable development. This reflection will then lead to the core of the ethical question of the meaning and the roles of technology for health and care. Especially, it will suggest a way to collectively build these meaning and roles; this way is in the opposite course of the techno-hubris, and of the economical, ecological, demographical and political disorders. "
