@article{Roth1997715,
title = "\{THE\} \{CURRENT\} \{HEALTH\} \{CARE\} \{ENVIRONMENT\} \{AND\} \{STAGES\} \{OF\} \{MARKET\} \{DEVELOPMENT\} ",
journal = "Gastroenterology Clinics of North America ",
volume = "26",
number = "4",
pages = "715 - 724",
year = "1997",
note = "",
issn = "0889-8553",
doi = "http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0889-8553(05)70327-7",
url = "http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0889855305703277",
author = "Bennett E. Roth",
abstract = "If one is to understand the current status and climate of the U.S. medical system, it is essential to place it in the appropriate historical perspective. One must look at how the medical system evolved into the current situation, what the characteristics of that situation are, and what can be expected in the years to come. During the first half of the twentieth century, the practice of medicine was simple and straightforward. Patients had direct relationships with physicians and had ultimate choice in whom to see. Most physicians were in solo practice and received payments from patients on rendering service. Fees were relatively small, and there were frequent instances in which payments could not be made and services were provided in exchange for goods, future payments, and, not infrequently, the mere promise of payments that never materialized. Nevertheless, most physicians survived economically and enjoyed a high regard in their communities. At the same time, the public's expectations of what medical care could provide was modest. Physicians were viewed as caring individuals rather than miracle workers. They practiced autonomously and made decisions without the benefit of complex testing and procedures. In general, medical care was sought only for serious illness. Hospitals existed in urban settings and served large population areas. After World War \{II\} and up to 1965, changes began occurring in the public's attitude toward medical care. With significant developments in medical technology; developments in drugs, most notably antibiotics; and the experience gained in treating casualties during the war, Americans sought and soon demanded more from their physicians, with growing expectations for diagnosis and treatment. At the same time, costs began to increase. Medical care was not only available to the rich, but also became regarded as a right to all. Health insurance was developed by hospital organizations and the medical profession. Patients paid only a portion of their bill, and the ever-increasing demand for services combined with the growth in payments by third parties allowed for progressive increase in prices. 7 During this era, there was a large migration to the suburbs with patients no longer wanting to travel long distances to receive medical and hospital care. A result was the growth of community hospitals financed by the expanding insurance payments supported by ever-increasing premiums, resulting in double digit inflation within the health sector. Before President Clinton's efforts at health care reform, President Truman was an earnest champion of reform to stem the tide of the “runaway” health care costs of the late 1940s, during which health care accounted for less than 4% of the gross domestic product. Meanwhile, unions and employers became involved in underwriting some of the costs of health insurance premiums, and health care first became a significant issue at the bargaining table. With the absence of checks on supply and demand, however, costs continued to soar. In 1965, Medicare was created. Health care was deemed a right for the elderly, the poor, and the disabled, and government was called on to provide the financing. Suddenly, even those unable to afford private insurance were now covered. Technology flourished fostered by the perception and demand of the public that the more physicians could do, the better they would be. To a large extent, that was true. Between 1965 and the early 1980s, dramatic technologic advances were made in the practice of surgery and noninvasive imaging such as endoscopy, ultrasound, and the early development of computed tomography scanning. These technologies were expensive and were, in large part, financed by the government and insurance industry. The concept of cost-based reimbursement flourished so that the more physicians charged, the more they were paid. Physicians were recruited by hospitals to bring and refer their patients. The more the physicians did and the longer the length of hospital stay, the greater the payment. Because the increased cost did not have a direct impact on the patients, there was little resistance to this philosophy. The new technologies led to a dramatic shift in the physician population. There was a large increase in specialists who could use and provide the new types of technology patients and hospitals desired. Eventually the “me too” philosophy of hospitals led to an oversupply of beds and unnecessary duplication of services. Business ultimately called a halt to this runaway growth. At a time when medical care was approaching 9% to 10% of the gross domestic product, industry, which was paying for much of the health care premiums, saw those costs threatening pretax profits to the extent that insolvency was threatened for some of the largest employers. In 1965, Chrysler Corporation reported spending 8% of pretax profits for health care benefits for their employees. This figure rose to 26% by 1982 with projections of up to 65%% by 1995 (M Brotman, personal communication). This drain on profits had to be curtailed and eventually led to the current managed care era beginning in the early 1980s. Despite these efforts, health care's growth as a portion of the gross domestic product continued to increase to 13.7% in 1994. The rate of growth, however, finally slowed from 0.5% per year to less than 0.1%% in 1994. 9 With the advent of the 1980s, constraints were initiated on hospitals and physicians. Initially, noneconomic controls appeared, such as peer review and utilization management. The early efforts to contain costs led to the origination of the first health maintenance organizations (HMOs) in California, soon to be followed by more pervasive development in other parts of the United States, such as Minneapolis. Economic constraints on hospitals were led by the federal government's development of prospective payment by diagnostically related groups. Suddenly, hospitals were no longer paid based on costs but received a relatively fixed payment commensurate with the patient's diagnosis regardless of services provided. Length of stay became a burden. The longer patients remained hospitalized, the more services provided and the greater the potential loss. Because this initial new payment paradigm did not affect physicians, there was an obvious divergence of goals between hospitals and physicians in the approach to patient care resulting in growing acrimony, which to some extent exists even today. Eventually, physicians suffered the same restrictions on reimbursement. Medicare instituted the resource-based relative value scale replacing payment based on usual and customary reimbursement. This change did reduce the dramatic discrepancies in payments for procedural versus cognitive skills but resulted in the reduction of all levels of reimbursement on what many would charge are unfair and erroneous principles. This was rapidly followed by the dramatic curtailment of payments from private insurance carriers, the rapid reduction and practical demise of the fee-for-service form of payment, and the development and growth of alternate payment strategies that now constitute the economic cornerstone of medical practice in the United States. At the same time, the Health Care Financing Administration initiated the concept of volume performance standards that placed inherent stopgaps on the overall payment for specific services believed to be in excess of predetermined quotas based on previous experience. This change resulted in further reductions in per capita payment for such services so as to remain budget neutral. With this background, the stage was set for the dramatic changes in the marketplace that now exist in medical care. "
}
